node.text:
Instant smiles 😊 (via @cruzysuzy)

This is a quokka, also known as the short-tailed scrub wallaby. It’s a little macropod about the size of a domestic cat. A quokka weighs 2.5 to 5.0 kg (5.5 to 11 lb) and is 40 to 54 cm (16 to 21 in) long with a 25-to-30 cm-long (9.8-to-12 in) tail.

It was first described by Dutch mariner Samuel Volckertzoon when he wrote of sighting "a wild cat" on Rottnest Island in 1658.

In the wild, the quokka’s roaming is restricted to a very small range in the South West of Western Australia, with a number of small scattered populations. One large population exists on Rottnest Island and a smaller population is on Bald Island near Albany.

📷 via @cruzysuzy #heartwarming #smile
📍Rottnest Island, Australia

node.text:
An orca during sunset in Alaska. 🐳  (Via 📸 @marysmark)

The killer whale or orca (Orcinus orca) is a toothed whale belonging to the oceanic dolphin family, of which it is the largest member. It is recognizable by its black-and-white patterned body. A cosmopolitan species, killer whales are found in all oceans and most seas in a variety of marine environments, from Arctic and Antarctic regions to tropical seas; they are absent only from the Baltic and Black seas, and some areas of the Arctic Ocean.

#Alaska #animals #photooftheday

node.text:
A recently unearthed video from the early days of the Atomic Age shows the raw power of nuclear weapons 💥

In the clip, a Mark 7 nuclear gravity bomb explodes deep underwater, but creates a column of water vapor more than half a mile high.

The test (code name: Wahoo), took place on May 16, 1958. The detonation point was the open ocean near Enewetak Atoll in the Marshall Islands. According to the Nuclear Weapons Archive, the Wahoo device was detonated at a depth of 500 feet in 3,200 feet of water. The bomb had an explosive yield of 9 kilotons, or about two-thirds the yield of the bomb dropped on Hiroshima, and yet was considerably smaller and more compact than the “Little Boy” bomb.

🎥: Atomic Tests Channel (YouTube)
